Theorem -- t27 Geometric Proof of the Metric Curvature Formula -- t28 Curvature as a Force between Neighbouring Geodesics -- t29 Riemann’s Curvature -- t30 Einstein’s Curved Spacetime -- t31 Exercises for Act IV -- tACT V Forms -- t32 1-Forms -- t33 Tensors -- t34 2-Forms -- t35 3-Forms -- t36 Differentiation -- t37 Integration -- t38 Differential Geometry via Forms -- t39 Exercises for Act V -- tFurther Reading -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn inviting, intuitive, and visual exploration of differential geometry and formsVisual Differential Geometry and Forms fulfills two principal goals. In the first four acts, Tristan Needham puts the geometry back into differential geometry. Using 235 hand-drawn diagrams, Needham deploys Newton’s geometrical methods to provide geometrical explanations of the classical results. In the fifth act, he offers the first undergraduate introduction to differential forms that treats advanced topics in an intuitive and geometrical manner.Unique features of the first four acts include: four distinct geometrical proofs of the fundamentally important Global Gauss-Bonnet theorem, providing a stunning link between local geometry and global topology; a simple, geometrical proof of Gauss’s famous Theorema Egregium; a complete geometrical treatment of the Riemann curvature tensor of an n-manifold; and a detailed geometrical treatment of Einstein’s field equation, describing gravity as curved spacetime (General Relativity), together with its implications for gravitational waves, black holes, and cosmology. The final act elucidates such topics as the unification of all the integral theorems of vector calculus; the elegant reformulation of Maxwell’s equations of electromagnetism in terms of 2-forms; de Rham cohomology; differential geometry via Cartan’s method of moving frames; and the calculation of the Riemann tensor using curvature 2-forms. Six of the seven chapters of Act V can be read completely independently from the rest of the book.Requiring only basic calculus and geometry, Visual Differential Geometry and Forms provocatively rethinks the way this important area of mathematics should be considered and taught.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aDifferential forms. 0aGeometry, Differential. 7aMATHEMATICS / Geometry / Differential.2bisacsh  aA Geometric Approach to Differential Forms.  aA Visual Introduction to Differential Forms and Calculus on Manifolds.  aCartan.  aDavid Bachman.  aEinstein.  aFaraday.  aGeneralized Stokes Theorem.  aGeneralized Stokes’ Theorem.  aGeneralized Stokes’s Theorem.  aJon Pierre Fortney.  aMaxwell.  aNewton.  aPenrose.  aPrincipia.  aPseudo-Riemannian Geometry.  aRiemann Tensor.  aRiemannian Geometry.  acurvature.  acurved surfaces.  aelectromagnetism.  ageneral relativity.  ageometric.  agravitation.  amanifolds.  amoving frames.  arelativity theory.  aspace-time.  aspacetime.  aspecial relativity.  avisual.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Mathematics 2021 Englishz978311075413108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Mathematics 2021z9783110753905oZDB-23-DMA08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073912140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978069121989940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691219899423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691219899/original  a978-3-11-073912-1  Princeton University Press